---
import Base from '../../layouts/Base.astro';
import { getCollection } from 'astro:content';

const results = await getCollection('results');
results.sort((a, b) => a.data.resultNumber - b.data.resultNumber);
---

<Base
  title="The Paper"
  description="Complexity-Sensitive Complementarity in Non-Isometric Holographic Codes. Cagle, A.R. 2026."
>
  <!-- Layout: PaperLanding.astro (from mockup_4_paper_landing.html) -->
  <main class="shell">
    <header class="frontmatter">
      <p class="masthead-eyebrow">Paper I</p>
      <h1 class="masthead-title">Complexity-Sensitive Complementarity in Non-Isometric Holographic Codes</h1>
      <p class="byline">Cagle, A.R., with Claude (Anthropic), computational collaborator</p>
      <p class="dateline">May 2026 &middot; arXiv:26XX.XXXXX</p>

      <div class="downloads">
        <a href="/paper/Paper1.pdf" class="dl-btn" download>Download PDF</a>
        <span class="arxiv-tag">arXiv:26XX.XXXXX</span>
      </div>
    </header>

    <section class="abstract">
      <h2 class="section-head">Abstract</h2>
      <div class="abstract-body">
        <p>We investigate the two-observer disagreement $\mathbb{E}|S_A - S_B|$ in Akers&ndash;Engelhardt&ndash;Harlow&ndash;Penington&ndash;Vardhan non-isometric holographic codes, with observers included via the Harlow&ndash;Usatyuk&ndash;Zhao cloning rule. Our central result is a <em>structural identity</em>: at leading order in $1/d_{\rm eff}$, the Haar-$V$-averaged observer-reduced state equals the diagonal of the bulk $A$-marginal in the observer&rsquo;s cloning basis, $\mathbb{E}_V[\rho_{R_A}] = \mathrm{diag}(\rho_A^{\rm bulk}) + O(1/d^2)$. Bulk-marginal coherences across distinct pointer values are projected out by the combination of HUZ cloning and Haar-$V$ averaging. This identity reduces the two-observer disagreement problem to a moment calculation of the bulk-marginal diagonal, whose scaling with observer dimension $d_B$ depends on the bulk state class. We carry out this calculation for two extreme classes. For random product bulk states we prove $\mathbb{E}|S_A - S_B| \to \sqrt{4(\pi^2/3 - 3)/\pi}\, d_B^{-1/2} \approx 0.608\, d_B^{-1/2}$; for Haar-random bulk states, $\mathbb{E}|S_A - S_B| \to \sqrt{2/\pi}\,/(d_M\, d_B^{3/2})$. Both exponents and prefactors are exact asymptotics. The integer exponent gap of $1$ between the two classes reflects exactly one power of $d_B$ per level of structural regularity in the bulk marginal. We verify the structural identity and both scaling theorems against full-simulation data at multiple independent levels, including out-of-sample tests at sub-$\sigma$ precision.</p>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section>
      <h2 class="section-head">Results</h2>
      <div class="results-grid">
        {results.map((r) => (
          <a href={`/paper/results/${r.data.resultNumber}`} class="result-card">
            <span class="result-num">Result {r.data.resultNumber}</span>
            <h3 class="result-title">{r.data.title}</h3>
            <p class="result-summary">{r.data.summary}</p>
          </a>
        ))}
      </div>
    </section>

    <section>
      <h2 class="section-head">Plain English</h2>
      <p>A non-technical explanation of what we found and why it matters. <a href="/paper/plain-english">Read "A Little Help for My Friends" &rarr;</a></p>
    </section>

    <section>
      <h2 class="section-head">How to cite</h2>
      <div class="citation-block">
        <div class="citation-inner">
          <p class="citation-text">Cagle, A.R., 2026. <em>Complexity-Sensitive Complementarity in Non-Isometric Holographic Codes.</em> arXiv:26XX.XXXXX.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>
  </main>
</Base>
